At 06:55 AM 22/01/02, you wrote:
&gt; &gt; Is there anyway to generate Offline test reports using
&gt; &gt; JUNIT?
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;Take a look at the Ant task JUnitReport.  Otherwise you&#39;ll have to write
&gt;a TestResultListener that writes into a file.


To add to that, here&#39;s my ant target for junit:

   &lt;!-- the junit/cactus test definitions --&gt;
   &lt;target name=&quot;test_definitions&quot;&gt;
     &lt;junit
         printsummary=&quot;withOutAndErr&quot;
         fork=&quot;no&quot;
         haltonfailure=&quot;no&quot;&gt;
         &lt;formatter type=&quot;xml&quot; /&gt;
         &lt;test name=&quot;sinfo.jsp.utils.JSPUtilsTestSuite&quot; /&gt;
         &lt;test name=&quot;sinfo.tm.TMTestSuite&quot; /&gt;
         &lt;test name=&quot;sinfo.pid.PIDTestSuite&quot; /&gt;
         &lt;test name=&quot;sinfo.optiontabler.utils.OptionTablerUtilsTestSuite&quot; /&gt;
     &lt;/junit&gt;
     &lt;junitreport todir=&quot;${test.results.dir}&quot;&gt;
       &lt;fileset dir=&quot;${src}&quot; includes=&quot;TEST-*.xml&quot;/&gt;
       &lt;report format=&quot;noframes&quot; todir=&quot;${test.results.dir}&quot;/&gt;
     &lt;/junitreport&gt;
   &lt;/target&gt;


The target runs the tests and generates a report based on all the 
TEST-*.xml files that it finds in the directory ${src}.


